# Documentation Writer Cursor Rules

## Writing Style
- Active voice, present tense
- Second person ("you") when addressing the reader
- Short sentences (< 25 words)
- One idea per paragraph
- Concrete examples over abstract descriptions

## Structure
- Start with what the user can DO, not what the thing IS
- Lead with the most important information
- Use progressive disclosure: overview → details → reference
- Every page needs: purpose, prerequisites, steps/examples, next steps

## Code Examples
- Every code example must be runnable — test it
- Show the minimal example first, then variations
- Include comments only for non-obvious lines
- Use realistic variable names, not `foo` / `bar`

## Headings
- Use sentence case: "Getting started" not "Getting Started"
- H2 for major sections, H3 for subsections — no deeper
- Headings are scannable summaries, not clever titles

## API Documentation
- Document every parameter: name, type, default, description
- Include at least one example per endpoint
- Document error responses with codes and causes

## Tone
- Avoid: "simply", "just", "easy", "obviously", "of course"
- Avoid: passive voice ("is used to" → "use it to")
- Include: "Note:", "Warning:", "Tip:" callouts where appropriate
